    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-24T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="653"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d653">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">781.003/23: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-24T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 24, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1041. An official of the Foreign Office tells us that the negotiations which have
                    been taking place in London regarding the relinquishment <pb facs="0872" n="861"
                        xml:id="pg_861"/> by Great Britain of capitulatory rights in Morocco was
                    initialed by the two delegations yesterday. It is expected that the agreement
                    will be signed some time next week by Eden<note n="6" xml:id="d653fn6">Anthony
                        Eden, British Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> and
                        Corbin.<note n="7" xml:id="d653fn7">André Charles Corbin, French Ambassador
                        in the United Kingdom.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The agreement provides that the relinquishment of the capitulations will be
                    effective on January 1, 1938. Provision is also made for the beginning of
                    negotiations regarding British commercial interests in Morocco.</p>
                <p>It may be presumed that upon the signature of the agreement with Great Britain
                    the French Government will transmit to our Government a copy of the agreement at
                    the same time requesting the opening of negotiations for the relinquishment on
                    our part of the capitulations in Morocco.</p>
                <p>Copy to London.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
